notesStmt.note: This biblical Psalter was created in French Flanders for a lady with Cistercian connections in the third quarter of the thirteenth century. Fourteenth-century additions for the use of a woman suggest that it continued to be used by female supplicants for some time after its creation. A prefatory cycle of ten full-page miniatures was also added in the fourteenth century, which complemented the original, and more traditional, series of ten historiated initials found within the Psalter.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Latin.

msItem.title: Calendar
msItem.note: Calendar one third full, graded in black, blue, and red; Egyptian days indicated; contents suggest Cistercian use; notable saints include Peter, archbishop of Tarentaise (May 8), Remigius (Oct. 1), Dionysius (Oct. 9), Malachy (Nov. 5), and Anianus (Nov. 17)

msItem.title: Added prayer and Gospel sequence
msItem.note: Text added in fourteenth century for use by a female supplicant; fols. 15r-16v: prayer to the Virgin; fols. 16v-17r: Gospel sequence from John 1.1-14

msItem.title: Biblical Psalter
msItem.note: Ten-partite biblical Psalter, with divisions at Psalms 1, 26, 38, 51, 52, 68, 80, 97, 101, and 109

msItem.title: Litany and collects
msItem.note: Fols. 205r-207r: litany; with six martyrs including Dionysius and Maurice; five confessors: Silvester, Martin, Augustine, Nicolas, and Benedict; eleven virgins including Pecina and Benedicta; fols. 207r-v: two collects

msItem.title: Added hymn to the Virgin
msItem.note: Hymn to the Virgin, added in the fifteenth century; incomplete, as last quire was lost after 1902, when Jacques Rosenthal recorded it ended with "...Salue salus humani generis Salue virgo dignior ceteris."

supportDesc.foliation: Modern pencil foliation lower right corners, rectos

p.formula: Quire 1: 12 (fols. 1-12); Quire 2: 1, is a singleton (fols. 13); Quire 3: 4 (fols. 14-17); Quire 4: 10 (fols. 18-27); Quires 5-13: 8 (fols. 28-99); Quire 14: 6 (fols. 100-105); Quire 15-19: 8 (fols. 106-145); Quire 20: 6 (fols. 146-151); Quire 21-27: 8 (fols. 152-207)
p.signatures: Occasionally found on rectos of first folio in quire
p.catchwords: Some lost during cropping; remains of catchwords visible beginning on fol. 35v

layoutDesc.layout: Layout does not apply to calendar (8.2 x 10.3 cm, five columns); calendar ruled in brown crayon, Psalter text ruled in lead

handDesc.handNote: Written in textura by later, fourteenth-century hand

decoDesc.decoNote: Ten full-page images in facing pairs with blank backs, added in the fourteenth century, on fols.18v, 19r, 20v, 21r, 22v, 23r, 24v, 25r, 26v, and 27r

Ten full-page miniatures, added in fourteenth century; ten historiated initials original to Psalter (3-8 lines); decorated initials in gold against blue and rose grounds with white foliate and animal details in calendar and introducing minor psalms (2-3 lines); psalm versals in alternating blue and gold with blue and red pen trails (1 line); geometric and foliate line fillers throughout; rubrics in red; text in black ink

decoNote.title: Initial "D" with David anointed by Samuel
Initial "D" with David pointing to mouth before the face of God
Initial "D" with Ahimelech being beheaded by Doeg
Initial "D" with the fool holding a club and biting a loaf
Initial "S" with David in water below Christ
Initial "D" with God the Father and Christ

binding.p: Rebound in the early twentieth century in burnt sienna velvet, and housed at that time in a telescopic case, by Léon Gruel, Paris; edges gilt; earlier binding described in Rosenthal catalog as having been brown calf, with monogram "P P L" within a series of four "S's" struck through with a vertical line

origin.origDate: Third quarter of the 13th century CE

history.provenance: Made for a lady with Cistercian connections in the third quarter of the thirteenth century; evidence includes initial with woman kneeling in prayer fol. 136v, and Cistercian saints in calendar
Second female owner suggested by fourteenth-century addition of prayers to Virgin for female supplicant, fols. 15r-17r
Jacques Rosenthal collection, Munich; 1901 dealer catalog 27, no. 74
Léon Gruel, Paris, early twentieth century; Gruel and Engelmann bookplate on front flyleaf i,v, inscribed "No. 63"
Henry Walters, Baltimore, purchased from Gruel between 1902 and 1931
history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters' bequest
